---
/**
 * Home page, and the site's only complete directory.
 *
 * It lists every section hub deliberately. There is no search on a static site,
 * so a hub nothing links to is a hub nobody reaches — 28 of 34 of them were in
 * that state before this page was rewritten, and the quality gate now fails if
 * it happens again.
 */
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import HouseholdCalculator from '../components/calculators/HouseholdCalculator.tsx';
import { LAST_VERIFIED } from '../data/federal';
import { stateList } from '../data/states';
import { stateSlug } from '../lib/slug';
import { PROFESSIONS } from '../lib/professions';
import { INSTRUMENTS } from '../lib/equity';
import { localTaxStates } from '../lib/local-tax';
import { PAIRS } from '../lib/formation-pairs';
import { states } from '../data/states';

const localStates = localTaxStates();

// The five gig categories and their platforms live in one shared module, so the
// home page and the /gig-tax-calculator/ hub never drift.
import { GIG_CATEGORIES as GIG, GIG_PLATFORMS as PLATFORMS } from '../lib/gig';
---

<Base
  title="MoneyScope — 2026 tax calculators for 1099, gig, and self-employed income"
  description="Free 2026 tax calculators. Self-employment tax, federal, state and local income tax, S-corp elections and equity compensation — with figures verified from IRS and state revenue sources."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year · verified {LAST_VERIFIED}</p>
    <h1>Tax calculators for people who <em>work for themselves</em></h1>
    <p class="tagline">Self-employment tax, federal, state and local income tax, and what to set aside — in one place.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Every rate, bracket and threshold on this site is checked against IRS and state revenue sources
    before it goes up, and the worked examples are calculated from those same figures rather than
    written by hand. Where a number could not be confirmed, the page says so instead of guessing.
  </p>

  <p class="section-label">Household tax calculator</p>
  <p>
    One calculation for everyone in the household and every kind of income — wages, self-employment,
    Social Security, disability benefits, a pension, a 401(k) drawdown. Add a person, add as many income
    lines as you need, and it works out the whole bill together. That matters because these interact: one
    spouse's freelance income can make the other's disability benefit taxable when it was not before.
  </p>
  <HouseholdCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Start here</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 and self-employment tax</a> — by state</li>
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck</a> — everything taken out of a salary</li>
    <li><a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">Quarterly payments</a> — what to send and when</li>
    <li><a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/">S-corp election</a> — does it pay for itself here?</li>
    <li><a href="/benefits-tax-calculator/">Benefits and retirement</a> — SSDI, disability, Social Security</li>
    <li><a href="/entity-tax-calculator/">Sole proprietor, S corp or C corp?</a> — compare on your numbers</li>
    <li><a href="/incorporation-tax-calculator/">Delaware franchise tax</a> — and whether to incorporate there</li>
    <li><a href="/business-formation-state-calculator/">Where should I form my business?</a> — every state compared</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="section-label">Two states, head to head</p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {PAIRS.map((p) => <li><a href={`/${p.slug}/`}>{p.h1}</a></li>)}
  </ul>

  <h2>Pay, offers and withholding</h2>
  <p>
    The questions that come up between paychecks, not at filing time — what a bonus really keeps, whether
    a raise beat inflation, what an hourly rate is a year, and whether the contract pays more than the salary.
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/w4-withholding-calculator/">W-4 withholding</a> — heading for a refund or a bill?</li>
    <li><a href="/bonus-tax-calculator/">Bonus tax</a> — flat 22% vs the aggregate method</li>
    <li><a href="/w2-vs-1099-calculator/">W-2 vs 1099</a> — compare two offers on take-home</li>
    <li><a href="/overtime-pay-calculator/">Overtime pay</a> — federal and California rules</li>
    <li><a href="/hourly-to-salary-calculator/">Hourly to salary</a> — convert a wage either way</li>
    <li><a href="/raise-calculator/">Raise</a> — is it a raise after inflation?</li>
    <li><a href="/marriage-tax-calculator/">Marriage penalty or bonus</a> — two incomes, single vs joint</li>
    <li><a href="/multi-state-tax-calculator/">Multi-state</a> — income earned across several states</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tax where you live and where you work</h2>
  <p>
    Two layers most calculators skip. Cross a state line to work and two states have a claim on the same
    wages. Live in one of twelve states and a city, county or school district taxes you on top of the
    state — {localStates.length} states do, in eight structurally different ways.
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/cross-border-tax/">Living and working in different states</a> — reciprocity, nonresident returns, credits</li>
    <li><a href="/local-income-tax/">Local income tax</a> — city, county and school district</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="section-label">Local income tax by state</p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {localStates.map((c) => (
      <li><a href={`/local-income-tax/${stateSlug(states[c].name)}/`}>{states[c].name}</a></li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>What your profession can deduct</h2>
  <p>
    Schedule C is the same form for everyone and the deductions on it are not. A signing agent's mileage,
    a driver's per diem, a minister's housing allowance that is exempt from income tax and taxed for
    self-employment tax at the same time:
  </p>
  <p><a href="/self-employed-tax-calculator/deductions/">The deductions checklist that applies to every business →</a></p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {PROFESSIONS.map((p) => (
      <li><a href={`/self-employed-tax-calculator/${p.slug}/`}>{p.name}</a></li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2><a href="/gig-tax-calculator/">Gig and platform income</a></h2>
  <p>
    Grouped by what you can deduct rather than by which app pays you, because that is what changes the
    answer — a Lyft driver and an Uber driver have the same tax question, and a driver and an Etsy seller
    do not. The <a href="/gig-tax-calculator/">gig hub</a> lays out every category:
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {GIG.map((g) => <li><a href={g.href}>{g.name}</a> — {g.note}</li>)}
  </ul>
  <p class="section-label">By platform</p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {PLATFORMS.map((p) => <li><a href={p.href}>{p.name}</a></li>)}
  </ul>

  <h2>Running a self-employed business</h2>
  <p>
    The economics behind the tax — what an hour of gig work really pays, what a mile costs, your seller margin,
    the rate to charge, and how much you can shelter for retirement.
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/gig-income-calculator/">Gig income</a> — real $/hour and $/mile</li>
    <li><a href="/mileage-deduction-calculator/">Mileage deduction</a> — the 2026 split rate</li>
    <li><a href="/vehicle-cost-calculator/">Vehicle cost</a> — real cost per mile</li>
    <li><a href="/seller-profit-calculator/">Seller profit</a> — Etsy, eBay, Shopify margin + tax</li>
    <li><a href="/1099-k-calculator/">1099-K reconciliation</a> — gross to taxable</li>
    <li><a href="/freelance-rate-calculator/">Freelance rate</a> — the hourly rate you need</li>
    <li><a href="/self-employed-retirement-calculator/">Self-employed retirement</a> — solo 401(k), SEP</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tax credits</h2>
  <p>
    The credits that phase in and out with income — where a small change can swing hundreds or thousands of
    dollars, and where getting the threshold wrong hurts most.
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/earned-income-credit-calculator/">Earned income credit</a> — refundable, up to $8,231</li>
    <li><a href="/child-tax-credit-calculator/">Child tax credit</a> — $2,200 per child under 17</li>
    <li><a href="/child-care-tax-credit-calculator/">Child &amp; dependent care</a> — 20–35% of care costs</li>
    <li><a href="/savers-credit-calculator/">Saver's credit</a> — for retirement contributions</li>
    <li><a href="/aca-subsidy-calculator/">ACA subsidy</a> — premium tax credit and the 400% cliff</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>More situations</h2>
  <p>
    Rental property, an early retirement withdrawal, working abroad, a second household income, an
    owner-operator truck, a creator brand deal — each taxed by its own rules.
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/rental-income-tax-calculator/">Rental income</a> — depreciation, Schedule E vs C</li>
    <li><a href="/retirement-withdrawal-calculator/">Retirement withdrawal</a> — early penalty, Roth conversion</li>
    <li><a href="/foreign-earned-income-calculator/">Foreign earned income (FEIE)</a> — the stacking rule</li>
    <li><a href="/second-income-calculator/">Second income</a> — is the second job worth it?</li>
    <li><a href="/trucking-cost-calculator/">Trucking cost per mile</a> — owner-operators</li>
    <li><a href="/brand-deal-tax-calculator/">Brand deals</a> — creators, and taxable gifted product</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Windfalls, gifts and inheritance</h2>
  <p>
    Money that arrives outside a paycheck is taxed by its own rules — a gambling win, a gift, an inheritance where
    the asset type decides everything. These never just say "taxable" or "tax-free".
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/gambling-tax-calculator/">Gambling tax</a> — winnings, and the 2026 90% loss rule</li>
    <li><a href="/lottery-tax-calculator/">Lottery</a> — lump sum vs annuity take-home</li>
    <li><a href="/w2g-tax-calculator/">W-2G</a> — 24% withholding vs your real tax</li>
    <li><a href="/professional-gambler-tax-calculator/">Professional gambler</a> — casual vs Schedule C</li>
    <li><a href="/gambling-social-security-calculator/">Gambling &amp; Social Security</a> — the hidden second tax</li>
    <li><a href="/gambling-aca-subsidy-calculator/">Gambling &amp; ACA subsidy</a> — the 400% cliff</li>
    <li><a href="/inheritance-tax-calculator/">Inheritance tax</a> — by what you inherit, with step-up basis</li>
    <li><a href="/estate-tax-calculator/">Estate tax</a> — the $15M exclusion</li>
    <li><a href="/gift-tax-calculator/">Gift tax</a> — the $19k annual exclusion and Form 709</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Investments and capital gains</h2>
  <p>
    What you owe on gains, dividends, interest and crypto — the holding period, the 0/15/20% long-term rates,
    the 3.8% surtax, and which lot you sell — federal and your state, including the states that tax gains differently.
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/">Capital gains</a> — short vs long-term, losses, NIIT</li>
    <li><a href="/cost-basis-calculator/">Cost basis</a> — FIFO, LIFO and specific-lot gain</li>
    <li><a href="/dividend-tax-calculator/">Dividends</a> — qualified vs ordinary</li>
    <li><a href="/investment-income-tax-calculator/">Interest income</a> — savings, CDs, Treasuries, munis</li>
    <li><a href="/crypto-tax-calculator/">Crypto</a> — coins, staking and NFTs</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Equity compensation</h2>
  <p>Each of these has one expensive mistake attached to it, and the pages lead with it:</p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {INSTRUMENTS.map((i) => (
      <li><a href={`/${i.slug}/`}>{i.label}</a> — {i.trap}</li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>1099 tax calculator by state</h2>
  <p>Pick your state for a page built on that state's 2026 income tax rules:</p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {stateList.map(([, s]) => (
      <li><a href={`/1099-tax-calculator/${stateSlug(s.name)}/`}>{s.name}</a></li>
    ))}
  </ul>
</Base>
